lution with such vitality and appeal precisely because it addressed those local issues. Among the archival records drawn on in the book are the testimonies and depositions of hundreds of men and women captured and tried by the Batista government. García also interviewed many of the leaders, combatants, laborers, and peasants who participated in various phases of the insurgency. The resulting study illustrates the development of methods of resistance, the evolution of varieties of rebellion, and how disparate social groupings emerged into a single revolutionary movement that swept away not only an unpopular government, but also an entire social system.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aGovernment, Resistance toxHistoryxCubaxMatanzas (Province). 0aGovernment, Resistance tozCubazMatanzas (Province)xHistory. 0aGovernment, Resistance tozCuba. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh1 aPérez, Louis A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertLynne Rienner Press Complete Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z978311078426840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978162637136140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781626371361423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781626371361/original  a978-3-11-078426-8  Lynne Rienner Press Complete Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK